review_blob:
Color: Clear, deep burnt amber color with black tones. Thin foamy white head with no lacing. 

Nose: Rich and pungent nose of cherries and soft malt. Gorgeous fresh fruit notes. 

Palate: Heavy weight. Big chewy malt, coffee, chocolate and a touch of cherry fruit toward the finish, but overall dominated by the massive malt character.

Color: Honey brown with white foamy head and heavy lacing. Lots of suspended, flocculated yeast. 

Nose: Soft and honeyed, caramel, yeast and bready notes. 

Palate: Thick and heavy palate; big caramel malt. Bready and doughy with a touch of coriander on the finish.

Color: Brown ale with amber tones. Off white foamy head and heavy lacing. 

Nose: Nice malty nose. A pleasant toasty graininess and a touch of soft grapefruity hops in the back. 

Palate: Velvety texture and medium weight. Caramel, toasted grain, pleasing malt. Touches of candyish sweetness and vegetal notes on the finish.

Color: Pale straw gold with a fizzy white head and nice lacing. 

Nose: Warm, toasty caramel and honey notes. A pleasant sweetness and the faintest hint of citrusy hops.

Palate: Maltly with dried grains and faint citrus peel. Very fresh and clean with a long, soft, malty finish.

Color: Cloudy, honey gold with a foamy tan ring and practically nonexistent head. 

Nose: Big and chewy raisiny notes with spicy cinnamon and caramel. 

Palate: Heavy caramel and pruny/raisin notes. Lemony pithy/pulpy notes. A refreshing effervescence and touch of milk chocolate on the finish.

Color: Cloudy golden beer with foamy white head and very light lacing. 

Nose: Fragrant with sweet citrus, toasty caramel and wet stone. 

Palate: Caramely sweet and pleasantly earthy. A light touch of vegetal hops on the finish. Simple, but tasty.

Color: Pale yellow gold. Off white fizzy head. 

Nose: Simple. Spring water and caramely malt. 

Palate: Thin. Nice malty character. No complexity whatsoever. Noticable absence of hops.

I cant dog this beer as much as I would like to. It serves a purpose. When you get done mowing the yard and want to swill something other than water it is great. It is light. You get malt and water. I cant complain. Not my favorite, but it doesnt taste bad.

Color: Burnt hazelnut with amber glints. Foamy off white head with heavy lacing.

Nose: Chocolate covered raisins. Heavy sweet malt. Toffee and light coffeeish notes. Toasted caramel.

Palate: Simplistic. Pruny with bitter chocolate notes. A very drying, tannic finish. Mid weight palate, but velvety nonetheless.

Color: Cloudy, nut brown with honey undertones. Foamy tan head and big lacing. 

Nose: Big chewy, raisiny and fragrant malty notes. Fresh box of Sun-Maid raisins. Milk chocolate.

Palate: Sweet raisins and rich malt. A faint vegetal hoppy note. Creamy and full weight on the palate. Pleasant drying tannins on the finish and the appearance of a nice bready note.

Color: clear, honey gold with foamy head and light lacing. 

Nose: Perfumey, with clover honey, warm toast and stewed apricot. 

Palate: A touch thin. Honey and barley bread, caramel and a slightly nutty finish. Overall, what it lacks in complexity and palate weight, it makes up for in drinkability--a tremendous session beer.

Color: Pale gold and cloudy with a foamy white head and nice lacing. 

Nose: A distinctively simple malty nose with fruity raspberry notes and nutty crushed walnut notes. A touch of coriander/orange peel in the background. 

Palate: Simple malty palate. The palate weight is a bit thin, but has some nice bready, yeasty notes before finishing with caramel and honey. The lack of body is made up in the fact that this is a great session beer.

Color: Murky brown, cloudy with foamy brown head and light lacing. 

Nose: Amazing sweet wine notes. Port-like on second pass. Heavy rancio, almost becomes cognac-like. Cinnamon, clove and caramel. Rich, fudgey oak. 

Palate: Dry sherry and Cognacais notes. heavy caramel, oxidized oak, firm tannins. Very dry and very rich. Old raisin, prune, rancio, dry, spicy, kiln-dried oak. Succulent finish. Sweet and rich. An after dinner beer.

Color: Chestnut with Ruby glints. Light brown foamy head with light lacing. 

Nose: Walnut and decaying walnut husks. Oxidized sherry notes. Stewed fruit and raisiny notes. 

Palate: Chocolate and winey fruit. Nutty sherry notes. Lush, soft, oaky tannins. Stewed red currant. Soft chocolate finish. Velvety with caramel.

Color: Amber, clear with white foamy head and medium lacing. 

Nose: Sweet and malty. Caramel and clover honey. Light mustiness. Reassuringly simple. 

Palate: Big bloody/copper notes. Bready Pumpernickel notes. Malty with a pleasant metallic twang on the finish.

Color: Honey gold, clear, with foamy white head and moderate lacing. 

Nose: Pungent nose. Toasted caramel. Marzipan. Fresh milled corn. Cornbread.

Palate: Copper. Fresh corn mash. Stewed white peach. Typical Belgian vegetal astrinigency on the finish and light sweetness. Medium weight on the palate. Perhaps a touch watery, but refreshingly so.
beer_name: Silly La Divine Belgian Double Blond Ale

review_blob:
Color: Cloudy yellow gold with a white fizzy head and some lacing. 

Nose: Delicious,, musty, bready malt, doughy yeast and faint coriander underlie the pervasive old citrus peel notes. 

Palate: Earthy, malty notes that verge on sweetness. Some yeastiness mid-palate. Nice vegetal and herbal notes mark the lightly spiced finish.

Nose: More intensely speaks of the sea than its Islay brother, this whisky-matured beer has notes of saltwater, toffee, chocolate and smoke. Surprisingly, this lacks the peat intensity of the Bowmore cask finished beer. 

Palate: The palate is oaky, smoky, salty and filled with charred oak and chocolate notes. Again, surprisingly, less intense than the Bowmore aged beer. However, it is better balanced and has a smoother transition throughout.

Nose: This nose is very reminiscent of Bowmore--ferny and vegetal peat, salt, and faint iodine mix with the stoutish notes of burnt caramel, bitter coffee and dark chocolate. 

Palate: Big toasty oak, espresso, smoky peat and continuing scotchy notes of cask, sea and earth continue through to the lingering oaky, peaty finish. 

Overall: As a scotch drinker and a beer drinker, I find myself in, well, a paradox. It is a bit overwhelming and intense for a beer and comes off as a bit unbalanced and disjointed. Bowmore is good whisky, but maybe not good beer.

Nose: This beer smells exactly like Glen Moray--honey, baked bread, light winey/oaky notes and a touch of faint smoke. There is a rich and chocolately stout note that undergirds the soft, light and slightly alcoholy nose on this beer. 

Palate: The palate continues the wonderful whisky notes, but develops rich, milk chocolate, caramel, big oak, and lightly bitter coffee notes. The finish lingers and reminds one of the finish on a good whisky. Warming, sweet and long.

Nose: Big coffee notes underscored by faint hops. 

Palate: Rich, luscious coffee and dark, bitter chocolate. Very faint, fruity hops. Classicly styled.

Nose: This IPA has a thicker, sweeter nose than its counterparts. Big and bready, almost doughy. Underlying is a fresh, light hoppiness. 

Palate: Richly malty, big musty punch. Light hoppiness and rich vegetal hops.

Nose: Fresh vegetal and grapefruity hops. Light sweetness as it warms. 

Palate: Very vegetal and grapefruity. Simplistic. Lingering, drying, vegetal notes as it fades to the finish.

Nose: Soft and hoppy, caramel and a touch of yeastiness. 

Palate. Straightforward amber style with loads of grapefruity hops. Caramely malt finishes.

Color: Golden brown with a fizzy white head. 

Nose: Asparagus. Fresh herbs. Citrus. Malt. Great musty notes. 

Palate: Wonderful effervescence. Citrus and sweet malt--almost bready. Soft and delectable. Noticably missing the lemony astringency on the finish of other Petrus beers.

Color: Dark brown with ruby glints and a foamy brown head. 

Nose: Big chewy malt. Musty and stinky with yeast. Horseblanket. 

Palate: Malty notes. Caramel. Red currants. Touch of old citrus on the finish. Well-balanced.
beer_name: La Bire du Boucanier Dark Ale

review_blob:
Color: Amber with foamy off white head. 

Nose: Nice and malty. The same theme of lemony, oaky notes that seem common in Petrus. Fresh and herbal notes on the backside of the nose. 

Palate: Musty, citrusy notes. Green strawberries. Long finish of dry malt and oak.

Color: Golden, toasty brown with a quickly dissipating, off-white foamy head. 

Nose: Old wheat bread, touch of chocolate, fresh oats and hay, and a soft yeastiness. 

Palate: Big, sweet, malty palate. Pumpernickel. Nice, light astringency on the finish rounds out the sweet palate of toasted grains.
beer_name: La Bire du Boucanier Red Ale

review_blob:
Color: black with brown/ruby glints. Foamy light brown head. 

Nose: Heavy sweet chocolate notes. Peaberry, bitter chocolate, oaky tannins and soft malt. 

Palate: Herbal and lemony, then quickly dosed with chocolate malt and an oaky finish.  There is a wonderful balance between the dark chocolate notes and the light astringency of the lemony notes.

Color: Nectar. Little to no white head. 

Nose: Deep, rich and spicy nose with a pleasant mustiness, spicy oak and soft, overripe mango. 

Palate: Initially sour cherry, lemony oak and tannin. Chalky sweet-tart notes. Pleasant acidity on the finish reminiscent of muscadine and wild honeysuckle vines.

This hazenut colored beer has little to no head. The nose is simple with sweet malt and a dank astringent note (like grapefruit in the basement). The palate is lightly oaked and malty, but tastes a bit thin and watery. The finish is lightly astringent and a touch hoppy.

This brew is thin black with glints of ruby. It has a light white head with light lacing. The nose has touches of light grapefruity hops blanketed by rich toasted grains and caramel. As it warms, herbaceous notes and light chocolate malt develop. The palate has more ale-like character with heavier hops, caramel and light malt which lead to the lightly bitter, weak coffee finish.

This Ale is hazy golden with a massive, foamy head. The nose is intense with sappy American Cedar. It is so intense, I can barely bring myself to drink it. The palate has a flash of fruity malt, which quickly bequeaths itself to the monstrous cedar. The finish is very dry with pine tar, cedar bark and freshly planed cedar.

This beer is dark brown with a light head that leaves nice lacing.  An amazing and complex nose of rich malt, and almost bourbon-like fruit. Caramel, butter, a touch of oak and stunning malt develop as it opens. The palate is creamy with malt, butter and caramel unlike any I have tasted. The finish is long and malty with hints of fruit.

Adequately described as a black ale, this beer has a foamy brownish head. The nose has leafy vegetal and berry aromas enveloped in dark chocolate malt. The palate is creamy with some notes of cocoa and subdued fruit. Toward the finish, the vegetal notes reemerge creating a lasting taste of maple and berries.

This brown-gold ale has a nonexistent head and a good deal of floculated yeast. The nose is heavy and sweet with clover honey and bready, yeasty aromas. The palate is a let-down after the intense nose displaying a very light body with heightened effervescence and some malty character. The malt fades into the watery finish.

This Lager is translucent gold with a light, fizzy white head. The nose is simplistic with light hoppiness and a touch of toasted malt. The palate is as simplistic as the nose with rather ordinary malt character and a hint of copper. The finish is almost nonexistent, but some lemony hops crisply round out this summer beer.

This roasted almond colored beer has a near perfect brownish-white, fizzy head that leaves a touch of lacing. The nose is incredibly malty with caramelized grains and hints of chocolate. The palate echos the intensity of the nose with massive caramel and nutty malt. The finish actually picks up a touch of hoppiness, which quickly fades into marzipan.

This yellowy-gold beer has a light foamy head with some lacing. The nose is light with stewed red currants and clear presence of rich, toasted malt. The palate is nicely astringent with some blood/copper notes and a touch of underripe plum which fades into the lemony, but cleansing finish. A touch of the copper note lingers. An excellent summer beer.

This beer is the color of young Sauternes and has a fizzy white head which lingers, but has no lacing. The nose is soft with notes of malt, horehound candies and subued tree fruit. The palate is lightly sweet, but well balanced. The malty notes fuse well with the lightly acidic fruit quality and the slight hops note. The finish is lightly prickly with some nice hops and sweet malt.

This oloroso colored beer has a quickly fading off-white head. The nose is heavy with burnt grains and toasted caramel. The palate is medium-bodied with notes of weak coffee and raspberries. A light fruit and malt sweetness lingers toward the finish.

This pale straw colored beer has a foamy white head with light lacing. The nose is almost non-existent, but there are light malty notes and a touch of fruity hops. The palate is very light and has notes of fruit and metallic copper. The finish is as non-existent as the nose, but some light maltiness is detected. Something about it makes it weird to drink.

This chocolate brown beer has a rich, foamy, light brown head with nice lacing. Soft fruits waft from the glass, surrounded by light caramel and toasted grains. The medium-bodied palate is creamy with light herbaceous hops and dried figs. The finish is silky with a touch of unsweetened chocolate and oak.

This inky black beer has a nice tan head. The nose is almost astringent with burnt malt and dark roast coffee beans. There is also a dustiness which reminds me of freshly gound chocolate malt. Despite the heaviness of the nose, there are some lighter characteristics that try to shine through: unsweetened chocolate, truffles and fruit. The palate is thick and heavy, but not as intense as the nose would lead you to believe. It is reminiscent of very watery, black coffee. The intense burnt grain note remains, however, and it follows through to the almost creamy finish. An easy to drink beer considering some of its intense characteristics.

This beer is pale golden with a light, fizzy head and gobs of flocculated yeast. The nose is musty with notes of Gruyere cheese, toasted meringue and sweet malt. The palate is straightforward with massive caramel, heavy malt and very faint hops as the finish quickly fades.

This cloudy, honey-gold beer has a bright, white head. The nose is yeasty with loads of heavy, sweet malt and light undertones of citrus hops. A slight touch of mustiness as it warms. The palate is medium-bodied with warm bread, soft fruits and light spice. The finish is once again yeasty, but semi-sweet with velvety malt and old lemons.

03/97 cork date. This beer has the color of tarnished copper and very little head. What little head there was disappears almost immediately. The nose is quite stunning. Rich earth, musty peaches, lemony oak, anise and fresh apples. The palate is dry with baked apples, old oak, stale bread and musty lemons. The finish is dry and ends abruptly, but is strangely appetizing and refreshing.

This hazy golden ale has a rich, tan head with a little lacing. The nose is brothy and pungent with intense perfumy mango seed notes, clove, bay leaves and a touch of sweet malt. The palate is very brothy, dry and continues the perfumey mango seed notes. As the finish approaches the dryness fades to sweet malt and citrusy hops.

This chestnut brown beer has a thick white head and heavy lacing. The nose is amazingly rich with charred oak, spiced apples, cinnamon, chocolate and a touch of raisin. The palate is dense with sweet chocolate covered raisins and dry wood-smoked barley malt. THe finish is a touch lack lustre given the amazing nose and palate, but it is creamy and rich with an afterthought of lemon meringue.

This honey-gold beer has a nice white head. The nose is yeasty and bready with touches of citrusy hops and copper that intermittently shine through. The palate is rich and honeyed with more bready notes and rich semi-sweet malt, toasted grains and clover. The finish tickles the tongue, but is nonetheless soft and honeyed with more sweet malt.
beer_name: Abbaye dAulne Triple Blonde Sur Lie

review_blob: This golden beer has a small fizzy head. The nose is light, crisp and sweet with green apple peel and a chalky sweetness. It is approaching jolly rancher smell, but not quite. The palate is more subdued with sweet, overripe apples and a touch of coriander which lingers toward the finish.
